erica are inevitable or insoluble.This essential introduction to Costa Rica includes more than fifty texts related to the country’s history, culture, politics, and natural environment. Most of these newspaper accounts, histories, petitions, memoirs, poems, and essays are written by Costa Ricans. Many appear here in English for the first time. The authors are men and women, young and old, scholars, farmers, workers, and activists. The Costa Rica Reader presents a panoply of voices: eloquent working-class raconteurs from San José’s poorest barrios, English-speaking Afro-Antilleans of the Limón province, Nicaraguan immigrants, factory workers, dissident members of the intelligentsia, and indigenous people struggling to preserve their culture. With more than forty images, the collection showcases sculptures, photographs, maps, cartoons, and fliers. From the time before the arrival of the Spanish, through the rise of the coffee plantations and the Civil War of 1948, up to participation in today’s globalized world, Costa Rica’s remarkable history comes alive. The Costa Rica Reader is a necessary resource for scholars, students, and travelers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Central America.2bisacsh1 aChant, Sylvia.1 aKirk, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarquardt, Steve.1 aMolina, Iván, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPalmer, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStarn, Orin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082238281240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382812.jpg 